@node "WhatIs" "What Is SendEvents?"

  @{b}What is SendEvents.br@{ub}

  SendEvents.br will allow the Thor user to send Thor Events and/or fetch News
  and Mail without the use of ConnectThor. The script supports POP3 and SMTP
  mail systems (user definable). It checks for any active Thor Events and, if
  found, pops up a requester that displays details of the Events (including
  which newsgroup (or EMail) the message is destined for). If you use Thor
  V2.31+, you also have the option to FTP Download Events from your favourite
  Aminet site.

  SendEvents.br presents the user with several options:

      POP3                   SMTP

  @{" Do All      " link "Do_All" 0}         @{" Do Both     " link "Do_Both" 0}
  @{" Send Events " link "Sending" 0}         @{" Get News    " link "Get_News" 0}
  @{" Get Mail    " link "GET_MAIL" 0}         @{" Send Events " link "Sending" 0}
  @{" Get News    " link "Get_News" 0}         @{" Download    " link "Download" 0}
  @{" Get Both    " link "Get_Both" 0}         @{" Cancel      " link "Cancel" 0}
  @{" Download    " link "Download" 0}
  @{" Cancel      " link "Cancel" 0}

  The Download button will only appear if there are any active Download Events.

  If there are no active Events waiting then a requester will pop up allowing
  you to collect news (both systems) and/or mail (POP3 only).
@endnode

@node "Features" "Features"

  @{b}Features@{ub}

  *  AREXX script that can be:

       Executed from a cli

       Attached to a DOpus (or Toolmanager) button

       Selected from a menu item.

       Included in your 'Link Up' script or tool

  *  Does not require Thor to be running.

  *  Has a user-configurable number of retries if mail/news servers are busy.

  *  Can be used with either a POP3 or SMTP systems (user-configurable)

  *  Presents the user with details of Events waiting to be sent:

       Real Name of addressee (if the addressee is in your user database)

       Name of Conference (EMail or Newsgroup) the Event is destined for

       Subject of message

       Join/Resign Conference Events

       Cancel a message

       Download Events (which can be FTP'ed)

  *  Logging of all actions

  *  FTP output to either a window or to the SendEvents log
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "System Requirements"

  @{b}Requirements@{ub}

  SendEvents.br requires the following (not included in archive):

    Kickstart 2.04 or higher
    rexxdossupport.library   (new for v1.5)
    rexxreqtools.library
    reqtools.library V38(+)
    rexxsyslib.library
    Thor 2.x+ installed and correctly configured for TCP operation.

  If you wish to make use of the Download Event type, then you will require Thor
  V2.3+ and FTPGet v1.2.

  FTPGet v1.2 is available from Aminet (comm/tcp/FTPGet1_2.lha). Please read the
  docs that are included in the archive. In particular, you will need to set the
  variables USERNAME and HOSTNAME in ENV: if not already set.

  You also need to have AREXX up and running.

  SendEvents.br has not been tested (to my knowledge) on anything other than an
  A4000/030 18mb with Workbench 3.0. It should work on Workbench 2.04/2.1/3.1.
  It will not work on Workbench 1.2/1.3.
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"

@{b}  Installation@{ub}

  Installation is very easy. Simply copy SendEvents.br to:

    (THORPath)rexx/bbsread/

  Copy cfgtcp to:

    (THORPath)s/

  Remember to substitute 'THORPath' with the contents of the file

    ENV:Thor/THORPath

  Note: You do not need Thor running in order to use this script, but putting it
  in the Thor/rexx/bbsread directory keeps all your Thor scripts together. Mind
  you, this is only a suggestion - you can put the script where ever you like!

  You will need to edit the following variables at the top of the script:


    @{" SystemName " link "SystemName" 0}       
    @{" MailType   " link "MailType" 0}       
    @{" Mailbox    " link "Mailbox" 0}       
    @{" NewsBox    " link "Newsbox" 0}       
    @{" MaxTries   " link "MaxTries" 0}
    @{" AutoParse  " link "AutoParse" 0}
    @{" LogOff     " link "LogOff" 0}
    @{" LinkDown   " link "linkdown" 0}
    @{" AminetSite " link "Aminetsite" 0}
    @{" FTPPath    " link "FTPPath" 0}
    @{" DLDir      " link "DLDir" 0}
    @{" LogOpt     " link "LogOpt" 0}
    @{" SE_Log     " link "SE_Log" 0}

  See the SendEvents.br script for a full example of all options.
@endnode

@node "SystemName" "SystemName"

@{b}  SystemName@{ub}

   This is the name of your TCP system as configured when setting up Thor using
   the System Configuration option.

   Examples:

      'Internet'
      'Demon'
      'Bloggs'

   or whatever wierd and wonderful name you have thought of to call your TCP
   system.
@endnode

@node "MailType" "MailType"

  @{b}MailType@{ub}

  This is the type of Mail system that you use with your ISP. The options are
  either POP3 or SMTP.

  'Demon Internet Services' users should set this to SMTP unless they are paying
  Demon extra to have a POP3 mailbox.

  Users of other ISPs should consult with their provider if they are not sure
  which system they are using.
@endnode

@node "Mailbox" "Mailbox"

  @{b}MailBox@{ub}

  This is the location of your mail box (on your system, NOT on your ISP's
  system).

  The location of your mail box is dependant on which mail system you are using
  (POP3 or SMTP).

  If you use POP3, then the incoming mail is stored (I think) in the following
  path:

    (THORPath)Data/BBS1/tcp_tmp/m.0

  This is the path (or something very similar) you should set for the MailBox
  variable.


  If you use SMTP, then the MailBox variable should be set to:

     UUMAIL:(username)

  where (username) is the same name that you used when you configured your
  Mailpacket in the System Configuration of Thor.

  Note: UUMAIL: is usually assigned, when you run your 'Startnet' script, to

          AmiTCP:usr/mail/

        If you store your incoming mail in a different directory, then you
        should use the appropiate path for the Mailbox variable.
@endnode

@node "Newsbox" "NewsBox"

  @{b}NewsBox@{ub}

  This is the location of the incoming newsgroup articles. This should be the
  same for both types of mail system (POP3 & SMTP).

  Set this variable to:

    (THORPath)Data/BBS1/tcp_tmp/n.0

  This assumes that you are using at least 1 socket (set in the Thor Systems
  Configuration under Type Options). Depending on how many sockets you have set,
  you will have the same number of files in the above path (after using Get News
  from SendEvents), each named n.? where ? = 0, 1, 2, 3, etc.

  Since you must use at least 1 socket, the script looks for n.0 and if other
  files are present, they will be processed as well.
@endnode

@node "MaxTries" "MaxTries"

  @{b}Maxtries@{ub}

  This is the number of times you want GetTCP and SendTCP to attempt to connect
  with your mail/news servers.

  If the servers are busy, SendEvents will keep trying to connect for the number
  of times that you set in this variable.

  (Demon users are well used to seeing the phrase '400 server busy' when trying
  to connect with the news server.)
@endnode

@node "AutoParse" " AutoParse  "

  @{b}AutoParse@{ub}

  This will allow the user to decide whether to parse any new mail and/or news
  articles automatically once collection is complete - regardless of the @{"LogOff" link "LogOff" 0}
  variable setting.
@endnode

@node "LogOff" "LogOff"

  @{b}LogOff@{ub}

  This variable allows you to decide if the option of logging off or not is
  presented once the sending of Events and/or mail & news collection is
  complete.

  The setting is either 'YES' or 'NO'.

  If you set this to 'YES' and select 'Log-off' from the requester AND if there
  is any new mail and/or news waiting to be parsed, you will have the option of
  parsing it at this time. If there are no new messages, you will receive a
  sympathetic response when you log off.

  The script will only do this if the @{"AutoParse" link "AutoParse" 0} variable is NOT set to 'YES'.

  If LogOff is set to 'NO' (or anything other than 'YES'), then the script will
  quietly exit once everything is complete, unless the @{"AutoParse" link "AutoParse" 0} variable is set
  to 'YES', in which case new messages will be parsed before the script exits. 

  YOUR MODEM WILL REMAIN ON-LINE if LogOff is set to "NO"!

  This option allows the script to be used in automatic systems without
  further intervention by the user once started.
@endnode

@node "Linkdown" "LinkDown"

  @{b}LinkDown@{ub}

  This is your link down command or script. You should specify the full command
  line that takes your system off-line.

  Example:

    'rx AmiTCP:bin/Link Down'
@endnode

@node "Aminetsite" "AminetSite"

 @{b} AminetSite@{ub}

  This is your favourite FTP site. I have used the Aminet site at
  ftp.netnet.net (which is fairly quick). You can use any site you like, but
  please allow sufficient time for new uploads to be distributed to the mirrors.
  I know that the main UK site (sunsite.doc.ic.ac.uk) can be a little slow at
  getting all the new files.
@endnode

@node "FTPPath" " FTPPath    "

  @{b}FTPPath@{ub}

  This is the path to FTPGet. If this file is not in your defined paths (i.e. C:
  or AmiTCP:Bin/ etc.), then the script will not be able to find it. It is best
  to define the full path here. It must end in ':' or '/'.

    e.g. AmiTCP:FTPGet1.2/
@endnode

@node "DLDir" " DLDir    "

  @{b}DLDir@{ub}

  This is the path of the location where you wish the downloaded files to be
  stored. It must end in either ':' or '/'.

    e.g. Downloads:
         Work:Downloads/
@endnode

@node "LogOpt" "LogOpt     "

  @{b}LogOpt@{ub}

  This is your preferred option for the output of @{"FTPGet." link "Credits" 0} There are two options:

  @{b}WINDOW@{ub}  will open a window to display the output from FTPGet. You will see
          the downloading progress of each file as well as any error messages.
          You will need to use the'CLOSE'gadget once FTPGet has completed
          downloading all files. I haven't yet figured out how to close a window
          from within AREXX. :(


  @{b}FILE@{ub}    will write the output of FTPGet to your @{"SendEvents.log." link "SE_Log" 0} Set
          this in the @{"SE_Log" link "SE_Log" 0} variable. This log will shown any error mesaages as
          well as details of all files downloaded.
@endnode

@node "SE_Log" "SE_Log"

  @{b}SE_Log@{ub}

  This variable over rides any setting you have made in the cfgTCP option from
  ConnectThor or Configuration/Systems Config/Type Options from within Thor

  This is the full path to your SendEvents.log file. All actions are recorded in this
  log file, including the output from GetTCP and SendTCP.

  If @{"LogOpt" link "LogOpt" 0} is set to FILE then this is where the output from FTPGet will go to.

  If LogOpt is set to WINDOW, then FTPGet output is sent to a window opened on the
  current screen.

  Default is 'Logs:SendEvents.log'.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  The script can be used in a number of ways.

  The simplest way to to run it from a shell window with the following command
  line:

    rx (THORPath)rexx/BBSRead/SendEvents.br

  Do not forget to use the actual path in place of (THORPath) in the command
  line.

  You could put the same line in your 'Link Up' script. This would allow you to
  start SendEvents each time you log into your ISP.

  Another option would be to set up a button or menu item (using Tool Manager or
  DOpus 4/5) which would run the script when required. You should consult the
  relevant instructions/manuals for the program you use.
@endnode

@node "Do_All" "Do All"

  @{b}Do All@{ub}  (POP3 only)

  This button will initate the collection of files from Download Events
  (if applicable), send active Events and then fetch your mail and news.
@endnode

@node "Sending" "Sending Events"

  @{b}Send Events@{ub}

  This button will initiate the sending of Active Events. It will not attempt to
  collect any waiting mail (POP3) or news.

  Once SendTCP has sent all Active Events, or SendTCP could not connect with
  your mail/news servers after the number of attempts set in the @{"MaxTries" link "MaxTries" 0}
  variable, and you have set the @{"LogOff" link "LogOff" 0} variable to 'YES', you will be advised
  whether the sending of Events was successful or not.
@endnode

@node "Get_Mail" "Get Mail "

  @{b}Get Mail@{ub} (POP3 only)

  This button initiates the collection of your E-Mail from your ISP. It will not
  attempt to collect news, nor send any waiting active Events.
@endnode

@node "Get_News" "Get News"

  @{b}Get News@{ub}

  This button initiates the collection of waiting news only. It will not attempt
  to collect any waiting E-Mail (POP3 only), nor will it send any waiting active
  Events.
@endnode

@node "Do_Both" "Do Both"

  @{b}Do Both@{ub} (SMTP only)

  OR

  @{b}Do All@{ub} if there are active Download Events.

  This button initiates the FTPing of files (if applicable), the sending of
  other active Events, followed by the collection of any waiting news.
@endnode

@node "Get_Both" "Get Both"

  @{b}Get Both@{ub} (POP3 only)

  This button initiates the collection of both mail and news. It will not send
  any waiting active Events.
@endnode

@node "Download" " Download    "

  @{b}Download@{ub}

  This button will only appear if there are active Download Events waiting.

  If selected, SendEvents will run FTPGet to get the requested files. If this is
  entirely successful i.e. without a single error, then all Download Events will
  be marked as DONE.

  A window will open that will display the output from FTPGet. If all goes well
  then the window will close automatically. The window may stay open if there
  was an error during the download. Click the 'CLOSE' gadget to close it.

  If there is an error during FTPing (file not found, access denied etc.) then
  FTPGet will continue with the remaining files (if any).

  You should check the Events list next time you run Thor as I am not sure that
  they are being set as DONE correctly if there was an error during downloading.
  I think it depends on where in the list of files that the error occurs. I am
  looking into the problem.
@endnode

@node "Cancel" " Cancel"

  @{b}Cancel@{ub}

  I'll let you figure this one out for yourselves.  ;)
@endnode

