@node "History" "History"

  @{b}History@{ub}

  V1.7   Added logging of all actions. Logs:SendEvents.log (user-definable)
         will record the output of SendTCP, GetTCP and FTPGet (but see below).

         Added an option to either view FTPGet's output in a window, or have it
         written to Logs:SendEvents.log (thanks Kevin). 

         Altered the order in which Events are now processed. SendEvents will
         now send waiting mail & news first, then get news and finally FTP any
         Download Events. (Thanks Shaun for the suggestion)

         Fixed a problem if your Thor TCP system name consisted of more than 1
         word. (Thanks again Shaun)

         Kevin Cowans provided a work-around for POP3 users. If using the
         GETBoth option and Mail collection failed, then GetTCP would exit
         without going on to collect news. SendEvents now checks if either was
         successful and goes on to collect the other (?).

         General tidy up.

  V1.6   Support for Download Events has been added. SendEvents will now FTP any
         requested files from your selected Aminet site. This option requires
         FTPGet V1.2 (..comm/tcp). Please read the instructions for this
         program carefully.

         Added the option to automatically parse new mail and news once
         downloading is complete.

         Two extra Event types have been added by Kevin Cowans. The script will
         now show 'Cancel Message' and 'Download File' type Events in the
         initial requester. Thanks Kevin.

         Changed the suffix to .br as it is a BBSRead script and Thor does not
         need to be running.

  V1.5   Removed the CmdPath variable from the user-define section. The scipt
         now looks in ENV:Thor for ThorPath and adds 'bin/' to it.

         Script now requires the rexxdossupport.library (V3.3 used)

         If required libraries are missing, and 'c:RequestChoice' (part of
         WB3.+) exists, a requester pops up to advise - otherwise script just
         quits.

         Script will now parse any waiting POP3 mail. Somehow managed to miss
         that bit.

  V1.4c  Fixed yet another bug (reported again by John Burger).

  V1.4b  Fixed problem where News was fetched after Send Events was completed
         (Only affects the POP3 people). Thanks to John Burger for finding
         the bugette.

         This version didn't make it to Aminet (Should be on Thor site though)

  V1.4a  I think I have finally sorted out the problem with 'retry' when sending
         events.

         The initial requester will now show all active events by type (EMail,
         Newsgroup messages, Join Conference, Resign Conference etc.).

         Added this AmigaGuide(tm) document.

         General tidy up of the code (again)

  V1.4   Not publically released

  V1.3c  Altered the layout of the buttons on the SMTP requester when active
         Events are present. The default (i.e. press 'Return' to action) is now
         'Do Both'.

         Fixed a couple of bugs.

           The 'Log Off' option requester was popping up if 'Cancel' was
           selected from the opening requester.

           I think I've got the 'Events successfully sent' message working.

  V1.3b Added a requester to advise if news/mail collection etc was successful,
         or not. This requester also presents the option of logging off or not
         after mail/news collection. This requester is optional - the user can
         decide if it appears or not.

         If you choose to log off, any new mail/news can optionally be parsed
         into the Thor message base.

         General code tidy up.

  V1.3a  Not publically released

  V1.3   Not publically released

  V1.2   The script will now display the number of active events, the addressee
         and the news group the message is destined for.

  V1.1a  (Not released) Removed some redundant configuration variables.

         I discovered that GetTCP and SendTCP both read the TCPExtConfig file
         from your system and therefore do not need most of the arguments to be
         stated in the script commands.

  V1.1   More or less a complete re-write. Following a suggestion from the Thor
         Team (thanks Petter), the script handles the search for events much
         better. It will now tell you how many active events (if any) are
         waiting.

         It now supports both SMTP and POP3 mail systems.

  V1.01  Added new variable (CmdPath) to set the path to SendTCP and GetTCP

         Added a new requester that pops up if no events are waiting.

  V1.0   First public release (a bit premature)
@endnode

@node "Updates" "Updates"

  @{b}Updates@{ub}

  I will attempt to fix any bugs that are reported to me via @{"E-Mail" link "Author" 0}.

  I will also consider the implementation of any suggestions received - if they
  are not beyond my fledgling programming skills.

  I will endeavour to upload the latest (bugfixed/enhanced) version to both
  Aminet and to the Thor support site at hstud6.cs.uit.no.

  I will post a message in alt.sys.amiga.thor whenever an update has been
  uploaded.


  @{b}Important@{ub}

  This will probably be the last update of SendEvents in it's present guise.

  I am working on V2.0 at the moment which will use a configuration file created
  by an Installer® script.

  I also plan to create separate versions of SendEvents for SMTP and POP3. The
  current version is getting too bulky. By splitting the versions, it will make
  each one smaller and, hopefully, a bit quicker.

  Finally, it has been suggested that I change the name of the script, since it
  now does more than 'send events'.

  'ProcessEvents' has been suggested by Kevin Cowans - I quite like that, but I
  would appreciate any other suggestions or thoughts on the subject.

  Finally, I would like some sort of positive feedback as to whether anyone is
  actually using this script (OK Kevin, I know you do ;)) ).

  @{b}Please@{ub} send me an @{"EMail" link "Author" 0} if you regularly use SendEvents. I see no point in
  uploading new/improved versions if no-one is using it. I will send a brief
  reply in acknowledgement.

  Thank you for listening.
@endnode

